  "prompt": "Vasoconstriction index of clobetasone butyrate?",
  "response": "Clobetasone butyrate is a topical corticosteroid used to treat inflammatory skin conditions. It primarily exerts its effects by reducing inflammation, itching, and redness. One of the mechanisms by which corticosteroids work is by inducing vasoconstriction (constriction of blood vessels), which helps reduce redness and swelling in the affected area.\n\nThe vasoconstriction index is a measure used to assess the potency of topical corticosteroids. It is determined by the degree of skin blanching (whitening) caused by the vasoconstrictive effect of the steroid.\n\nClobetasone butyrate is generally considered to be a **medium-potency** corticosteroid. Its vasoconstriction index falls in the range of mid-level potency, meaning it provides a balanced anti-inflammatory effect with a moderate degree of vasoconstriction. It is less potent than very high-potency steroids like clobetasol propionate but stronger than mild steroids like hydrocortisone.\n\nFor specific numerical values of the vasoconstriction index, you would need to refer to clinical studies or pharmacopeial data, as it may vary slightly depending on the concentration, formulation, and method of assessment.",
